        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">
        Out went Odeo, in came Twitter
        </h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
        Twitter began with a podcasting company that ran out of luck. In 2005, Evan Williams and Noah Glass co-founded a startup called Odeo, aiming to capitalize on the trend of podcasting. The idea was to become the central hub for audio content. But with the announcement of iTunes’s native support for podcasts, Apple effectively obliterated Odeo’s entire market potential overnight. 
          </p>
        </mj-text> 

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/jack-dorsey-first-tweet-nft-sale.jpg" alt="Dorsey's first tweet was sold as an NFT for $2.9M in 2021. It was purchased by a buyer using the Ethereum cryptocurrency" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>
            Dorsey's first tweet was sold as an NFT for $2.9M in 2021. It was purchased by a buyer using the Ethereum cryptocurrency. Credits: Odeo/Twitter</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            At that time, Jack Dorsey, a software engineer at Odeo, had been toying with an idea of a <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-07-06-2025-status-sharing-platform" target="_blank">status-sharing platform</a> where people could post short updates in real time. He pitched the concept, and Evan Williams made a bold move. He returned $5Mn in seed funding to Odeo’s investors, shelved the podcasting ambition, and threw the company’s weight behind this project. 
            </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         When Twitter first launched, no one quite knew what to make of it. Reviews were mixed. But as time passed, Twitter began to carve a niche, especially at tech events like South by Southwest (SXSW) in 2007, where real-time updates became a hit among attendees. It became a space for breaking news, influencer rants, and eventually, a political stage. 
          </p>
         
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
    </mj-section>

